1. Install Windows Server on a virtual machine using VirtualBox or VMware and take a screenshot of the desktop after the installation completes.
=>Download the Windows Server ISO (e.g., 2022/2025 evaluation from Microsoft Evaluation Center).
Install VirtualBox and its Extension Pack.
Create a new VM:
Name: e.g., "WinServer-DC".
Type: Microsoft Windows, Version: Windows Server (64-bit).
RAM: Minimum 4-8 GB (recommended 8+ GB).
CPU: 2-4 cores.
Hard Disk: Create new VDI, dynamically allocated, 60-100 GB+.
Storage: Attach the ISO to the virtual optical drive.
Enable EFI if needed for newer versions.

Start the VM and boot from the ISO.
In the installer:
Select language, time, keyboard → Next.
Click Install Now.
Choose edition (e.g., Windows Server Datacenter with Desktop Experience for GUI).
Accept license terms.
Custom install → Select the virtual disk → Next (installation proceeds, VM may restart multiple times).
Set administrator password and complete initial setup.

2. Open Server Manager and use the 'Add roles and features' wizard to install the Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) role. Document each step with a short description and screenshot.
=> It launches automatically or search for it in Start. Dashboard view shows local server info.
Add Roles and Features:
Click Manage → Add Roles and Features (top right).
Before you begin: Review notes → Next.

Installation Type: Select Role-based or feature-based installation → Next.
Server Selection: Select your local server → Next.
Server Roles: Check Active Directory Domain Services. A popup appears for additional features (e.g., management tools) → Click Add Features.
Features: No additional needed usually → Next.
AD DS: Review info → Next.
Confirmation: Review selections → Click Install. Progress shown; server may need restart.

Screenshots Description (in practice):

Wizard welcome / role selection screen with AD DS checkbox highlighted.
Confirmation page listing AD DS + dependencies.
Post-install: Notification flag in Server Manager with "Promote this server..." link.=>

3.Promote your Windows Server to a Domain Controller by creating a new forest with a root domain name of your choice (e.g., mycollege.local). List the options you selected during the configuration.
=>Promote your Windows Server to a Domain Controller by creating a new forest with a root domain name of your choice (e.g., mycollege.local). List the options you selected during the configuration.
After AD DS installation:

In Server Manager, click the yellow notification flag → Promote this server to a domain controller. This launches the AD DS Configuration Wizard.

Configuration Options Selected (example for new forest):

Deployment Configuration: Add a new forest → Root domain name: mycollege.local → Next.
Domain Controller Options:
Forest functional level: Windows Server 2016/2022/2025 (or highest compatible).
Domain functional level: Same.
DNS server: Checked (installs integrated DNS).
Global Catalog: Checked.
DSRM password: Set a strong password.

DNS Options: Default (delegation if applicable; usually none for new forest).
Additional Options: NetBIOS domain name (e.g., MYCOLLEGE) auto-filled or customized.
Paths: Default database, log files, and SYSVOL paths (C:\Windows\NTDS, etc.).
Review Options: Verify all settings.
Prerequisites Check: Should pass; fix any warnings.
Click Install. Server reboots automatically.

4. Create two new user accounts and one group in Active Directory Users and Computers. Assign both users to the group and describe how you did it.<br><br><em><strong>Hint:</strong> Use the 'Users' container and right-click options in ADUC.</em>
=>Steps (Hint followed):

Open Active Directory Users and Computers (dsa.msc via Run or search).
Expand the domain (mycollege.local).
Navigate to the Users container.

Create Group:

Right-click in Users container → New → Group.
Group name: e.g., "LabStudents".
Group scope: Global (default).
Group type: Security.
Click OK.

Create Users:

Right-click in Users container → New → User.
First user: Full name "Student One", User logon name "student1@mycollege.local" (or sAMAccountName "student1").
Set password (e.g., strong one), uncheck "User must change password at next logon" if desired.
Finish.

Repeat for second user: "Student Two" / "student2".

Assign Users to Group:

Open properties of "LabStudents" group → Members tab → Add → Enter "student1" and "student2" → Check names → OK.
(Alternatively: Edit each user's Member Of tab → Add the group.)

This completes the lab. Users are now members of the group for permission assignment later. Verify in ADUC by refreshing and checking group membership.
